Rules:
Rule 1: Preserve one shared backend. Core constitutional behavior lives in shared Python modules and is reused by CLI, GUI, and examples.
Rule 2: Do not fork writer/judge logic per interface. All interfaces must call `run_constitutional_turn`.
Rule 3: Reuse shared config and LiteLLM client helpers instead of rebuilding provider logic in each interface.
Rule 4: Ask for clarification before making large repo-wide behavior changes when requirements are ambiguous.
Rule 5: Update `README.md` and `README.llm` together when public config, CLI, GUI, or engine behavior changes.
Rule 6: Never expose real API keys in code, docs, logs, examples, or committed config files.
Rule 7: Keep docstrings current in Python modules and keep JS function comments aligned with behavior.

<ReadMe.LLM>

<library_description>
This repository provides a constitutional AI package with one shared engine and multiple interfaces.

Purpose:
- run writer/judge constitutional loops over user prompts
- support sequential and parallel rule-evaluation modes
- route model calls through LiteLLM
- expose the same core behavior through CLI, GUI server, and Python imports

Main components:
- `constitutional_ai.engine`: core constitutional loop (`run_constitutional_turn`)
- `constitutional_ai.config`: load/merge/save config and migrate legacy OpenAI-only configs
- `constitutional_ai.client`: shared LiteLLM request + model-list helpers
- `constitutional_ai.models`: dataclasses for messages and transcripts
- `constitutional_ai.cli`: command-line interface
- `constitutional_ai.server`: GUI + HTTP API wrapper around shared engine
- `launch_gui.py`: bootstrap script for local GUI setup

Key architecture constraint:
- there is one backend core. Interfaces should adapt input/output only.
</library_description>

<context_1>
<context_1_description>
Core engine entrypoint for one constitutional reasoning turn.
</context_1_description>

<context_1_function>
run_constitutional_turn(
    *,
    user_text: str,
    thread_messages: list[ChatMessage],
    config: AppConfig,
    on_event: Callable[[TurnEvent], None] | None = None,
    should_stop: Callable[[], bool] | None = None,
) -> TurnTranscript
</context_1_function>

<context_1_notes>
- Generates an initial writer draft.
- Evaluates rules via judge.
- Sequential mode evaluates rules one-by-one with per-rule revisions.
- Parallel mode evaluates all rules in parallel, critiques failing rules in parallel, then performs one combined revision per round.
- Returns structured transcript data in `writer.drafts`, `judge.checks`, `run.events`, `usage`, `duration_ms`, and `final`.
- Does not require provider-side model listing before a run; unsupported providers and local models can still run through manual model entry.
</context_1_notes>
</context_1>

<context_2>
<context_2_description>
Configuration loading and persistence used by CLI, GUI server, and scripts.
</context_2_description>

<context_2_function>
load_config(path: str | Path | None = None) -> AppConfig
</context_2_function>

<context_2_related_functions>
save_config(config: AppConfig, path: str | Path | None = None) -> Path
merge_config(base: AppConfig, payload: dict[str, Any] | None) -> AppConfig
set_config_value(base: AppConfig, key_path: str, value: Any) -> AppConfig
update_config_value(path: str | Path | None, key_path: str, value: Any) -> Path
</context_2_related_functions>

<context_2_notes>
- Config default path: `~/.constitutional_ai/config.json`.
- Legacy flat settings like `api_key`, `base_url`, `writer_model`, and `judge_model` are migrated into the new LiteLLM structure on load.
- Runtime settings contain:
  - provider credentials
  - separate writer endpoint settings
  - separate judge endpoint settings
  - runtime parameters such as temperature, token limit, execution mode, and time budget
- Environment variables override saved credentials for the matching provider.
- `api_base` is optional and supports custom endpoints and local servers.
</context_2_notes>
</context_2>

<context_3>
<context_3_description>
Primary message model used for thread history.
</context_3_description>

<context_3_function>
ChatMessage(
    role: Literal["user", "assistant"],
    content: str,
    at: str = now_iso()
)
</context_3_function>

<context_3_notes>
- Use `ChatMessage` for thread inputs to `run_constitutional_turn`.
- Convert to chat-completions message format internally via `to_openai()`.
- Validate untrusted mappings with `ChatMessage.from_mapping`.
</context_3_notes>
</context_3>

<context_4>
<context_4_description>
CLI interface for single-turn and interactive use.
</context_4_description>

<context_4_function>
constitutional-ai run --prompt "<text>" [--config PATH] [--rules-file PATH]
                      [--writer-provider PROVIDER] [--writer-model MODEL]
                      [--judge-provider PROVIDER] [--judge-model MODEL]
                      [--openai-api-key KEY] [--anthropic-api-key KEY] ...
                      [--execution-mode sequential|parallel]
                      [--parallel-max-iterations N] [--max-iteration-ms MS]
                      [--temperature FLOAT] [--max-tokens N] [--timeout-ms MS]
                      [--show-metrics] [--json]

constitutional-ai chat [--config PATH] [same provider/runtime overrides as run]

constitutional-ai config set --key <dotted.path> [--value <string> | --json-value <json>]
                             [--config PATH] [--show] [--redact-key]
</context_4_function>

<context_4_notes>
- `run` executes one turn and prints final answer or transcript JSON.
- `chat` maintains local conversation history and calls the same shared engine each turn.
- Provider-specific credentials are explicit CLI flags, matching the config schema.
- Config dotted paths now use nested settings such as `settings.writer.provider` and `settings.credentials.openai_api_key`.
</context_4_notes>
</context_4>

<context_5>
<context_5_description>
GUI server and HTTP endpoints.
</context_5_description>

<context_5_function>
Server entrypoint:
constitutional-ai-gui [--host 127.0.0.1] [--port 8765] [--config PATH] [--no-open]

HTTP endpoints:
GET  /api/config
POST /api/config
POST /api/turn-stream
POST /api/turn-cancel
POST /api/models
POST /api/test-connection
POST /api/turn
</context_5_function>

<context_5_notes>
- The GUI has one `Settings` tab with internal left-nav sections: credentials, writer model, judge model, parameters, and system prompts.
- `GET /api/config` returns redacted config plus credential source metadata.
- `POST /api/config` merges and persists config updates.
- `POST /api/turn-stream` streams run-stage events and the final turn result.
- `POST /api/turn-cancel` requests cooperative cancellation of an active streamed turn.
- `POST /api/models` uses LiteLLM model discovery for the requested role when supported by LiteLLM/provider.
- `POST /api/test-connection` runs a lightweight completion against the requested role config.
</context_5_notes>
</context_5>

<context_6>
<context_6_description>
Shared LiteLLM request client.
</context_6_description>

<context_6_function>
chat_completion(
    *,
    endpoint: ModelSettings,
    credentials: ProviderCredentials,
    messages: list[dict[str, str]],
    temperature: float,
    max_tokens: int,
    timeout_ms: int,
) -> CompletionResult

list_models(
    *,
    endpoint: ModelSettings,
    credentials: ProviderCredentials,
    timeout_ms: int,
) -> ModelListResult
</context_6_function>

<context_6_notes>
- `chat_completion()` is the shared LiteLLM call path for writer, judge, and server test requests.
- `list_models()` uses LiteLLM `get_valid_models(check_provider_endpoint=True, custom_llm_provider=...)` when supported.
- GUI falls back to manual text entry when model discovery is unsupported or returns no models.
- Never log or return raw credentials.
</context_6_notes>
</context_6>

<maintenance_policy>
When changing any of the following, update BOTH `README.md` and `README.llm`:
- engine behavior or signatures
- config fields/defaults/migration
- CLI commands/options
- GUI server endpoints or settings UX
- data models used in public examples
</maintenance_policy>

</ReadMe.LLM>
